The study of rhetoric, as has been said, did not gain any ground in Italy, or, rather, among the Romans, until after the subjection of Lower Italy. Greek rhetoricians came to Rome, either at personal invitation, or because of the opening that they faucied they saw for themselves at the capital of the natiou. The increasing power and demand they gained gradually led up to the demand for teachiug rhetoric in Latin. There was strong oppo- sition, but the opposition gradually gave way.
